    Easy Sweet & Sour Salmon Traybake

    You'll love this easy traybake dinner, which only takes 10 minutes to prep. You'll coat responsibly-sourced salmon and vibrant pak choi with a homemade sweet & sour sauce. Brown rice, crunchy mangetout and sesame seeds complete the dish.
    Cook time: 35 mins
    Cuisine: Asian
    Food group: Fish
    Key ingredient: Responsibly-sourced salmon fillet
    Allergens: Fish, Sesame, Soya

    Ingredients

    • 2 carrot
    • 25g honey
    • 160g mangetout
    • 1 onion
    • 2 pak choi
    • 2 tbsp rice wine vinegar
    • 4 salmon fillets (Fish)
    • 1 tbsp tamari (Soya)
    • 1 tbsp cornflour
    • 4 tbsp tomato ketchup
    • 140g tinned pineapple
    • 1 tsp sesame seeds (Sesame)
    • 200g brown rice

    Nutritional Information

    Calories: 678
    Protein: 38g
    Carbs: 65g
    Fat: 28g

    Cooking Instructions

    Before you start
  • Preheat the oven to 240C / fan 220C / gas 9 Bring a large saucepan filled with salted water to a boil Pull out a measuring jug, a sieve, a large baking dish & a small mixing bowl
  • Get the rice on
    • Add the rice to the saucepan and boil for 25-30 mins, until cooked, then drain
  • Roast the salmon
    • Cut the onion into wedges. Cut the carrots into 1cm half-moons. Cut the pak choi into bite-sized pieces. Drain the pineapple, reserving 100ml of the juice
    • Add the onion, carrots and pineapple chunks to the large baking dish (we used a 35cm baking dish). Drizzle with 2 tsp oil and season with salt and pepper. Toss to coat. Lay the salmon on top, skin-side down, drizzle with 1 tsp and season. Bake for 15 mins
  • Meanwhile, make the sweet & sour sauce
    • Add the pineapple juice, ketchup, tamari, cornflour, honey and vinegar to the small mixing bowl and mix well
  • Last bits
    • Once the salmon has been roasting for 15 mins, coat the salmon and veg with the sweet & sour sauce
    • Return to the oven for a further 5 mins, until the salmon is cooked through
    • After 5 mins, remove the salmon and add the mangetout and pak choi. Return to the oven for another 3 mins, or until the sauce has thickened
  • Plate up
    • Check your fish is cooked through; it should be steaming hot, opaque and separate easily with a fork
    • Serve the rice topped with the salmon and veg. Sprinkle over the sesame seeds
